Our human urge is to judge and criticize anything we see and experience, especially with the rise of social media, where we face thousands of opinions daily, each associated with a face and identity. The number of opinions we are given can be an amazing source of information that can help us make informed decisions about the types of video games we play, the foods we eat, and the movies we watch. However, there exists a dark side to these reviews that many people overlook, and this is prevalent in all forms of media criticism. 

Many people who write reviews do not realize the power they have to influence others, and this can often make or break the success of any media franchise or restaurant. This is especially a worry in video games because bad reviews can often cost companies millions of dollars, as people who see a lower score on a video game are usually less likely to play that game. Video game review sites like IGN, Gamespot, and Metacritic have already realized this and have taken a few ineffective measures to avoid the damaging effects of a single review. For example, Metacritic has a user review score along with the critic score, which allows thousands of users to help decide on a score instead of a single critic who may be misinformed, as mentioned in other blog posts on this page. However, a more worrying aspect of reviews can be found on sites that are not strictly meant to criticize, like YouTube, where anyone can post an opinion. Creators who post on websites like YouTube can certainly make an impact if they have a big enough audience.

A good example of this is not found in video game criticism but rather in food. Dave Portnoy has built his legacy off of pizza reviews on YouTube. Each of his videos garner millions of views, and when he visits a pizza place, a bad score often puts the restaurant under. Similarly to video games, one score from one individual after “one bite” is enough to prevent a small business from ever having the chance to improve and be successful. In my opinion, this is not a fair way to review anything, but what is? For an answer, we can look into the past.

![][image1]  
*Figure 1: David Portnoy*

Criticism is not a new concept. It has existed since the Michelin Guide was first published in the 1900s. But with the popularization of modern dining in the 1950s, food journalism became extremely popular, with Craig Claiborne, a classically trained food journalist, standing at the helm of the movement. Craig worked to develop the four-star food ranking system and did not take his responsibility to give an objective review lightly. He had a set of rules when he wrote his reviews and I believe they can be applied when reviewing any media.  

![][image2]  
*Figure 2: Craig Clayborne*

Craig Claiborne’s Rules

1. Refuse anything for free or handouts.  
2. Remain as anonymous as possible.  
3. Eat at the Restaurant Multiple Times.

These rules on the surface are fairly simple, but we can see how creators who review media online do not follow them at all. For example, we have seen many creators hide sponsorships from companies and pretend they just really like the product to seem more genuine. Youtuber ProSyndicate, for example, was a prolific CS:GO YouTuber who would post videos where he would gamble on websites he was sponsored by without revealing any sponsorship and fixing his odds to make people who watch his videos more likely to play on those sites. Looking at Craig's second point, we can see that the whole point of YouTube itself is not anonymous; creators often have to make their brand as loud as possible to stand out among the crowds of people chasing the same dream, and when reviewing anything, their brand is often more important than the video game that they are reviewing and playing. Finally, plenty of creators only play through a video game once, or sometimes they don’t even finish it at all, and they proclaim how bad the game is. Without giving the game multiple playthroughs, you do not truly get to understand the game and tie a fair score to it.   

![][image3]  
*Figure 3: ProSyndicate*

Overall, it's impossible to expect our favorite creators to follow the standards followed by professional food journalists. However, as consumers, we have the choice to make the correct decisions and examine reviews objectively to see if there are major flaws in the score. Hopefully, this blog will spread awareness of the issue and make people think twice before listening to critic websites like IGN and critics like Dave Portnoy.
